items.abstract: <jats:p>Mid urethral sling is the standard in SUI treatment. Nevertheless, the risk of reoperation reaches 9%. There is no consensus as to the best treatment option for complications. A question is raised: what is the optimal way to achieve the best result in patients after primary failure? The aim of the study was to evaluate the outcomes of repeat MUS surgery in patients after excision of the sling with recurrent SUI. We compared its effectiveness with uncomplicated cases treated with TVT. 27 patients who underwent the repeated MUS and 50 consecutive patients after primary TVT were enrolled in the study. After 6 months, we have found that 24 (88.46%) patients from repeat sling group and 48 (96%) patients after primary sling were dry (1-hour pad test, 2 g or less). The difference between groups was not significant. We showed statistically significant improvement of quality of life in both groups. In conclusion, we showed that repeated sling after MUS excision is almost as effective as primary MUS. We postulate that sling excision and repeated MUS may be the best option for persistent SUI and/or complications after MUS procedures. Further multicenter observations are ongoing as to provide results on bigger group of cases.</jats:p>
title: The Outcome of Repeated Mid Urethral Sling in SUI Treatment after Vaginal Excisions of Primary Failed Sling: Preliminary Study

<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
				<jats:p> Symmetrically 1,5 bridged cyclotetra(λ<jats:sup>3</jats:sup> -phosphazanes) 2a, b are formed from cyclotri-(λ<jats:sup>3</jats:sup> -phosphazanes) 1a, b and heptamethyldisilazane. Substitution of halogens at P<jats:sup>3</jats:sup> and P<jats:sup>7</jats:sup> in 2a, b by alkoxy or phenoxy substituents is achieved with alcohols in the presence of triethylamin to give 2c, d. NMR spectroscopy shows 2a, b to exist as isomers A or B, whereas for 2c, d additional asymmetric isomers like C or D are assumed.</jats:p>

				<jats:p> The compounds Pd(PPr<jats:sup>i</jats:sup>3)<jats:sub>n</jats:sub> (n = 2 or 3) and Pd(PMePh<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>)4 react with CS<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> to give the mononuclear complexes (PR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>Pd(η<jats:sup>2</jats:sup> -CS<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>). In the reactions of Pd(PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)<jats:sub>4</jats:sub> and Pd(PMe<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>Ph)<jats:sub>4</jats:sub> with CS<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> binuclear complexes [(PR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)Pd(S<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>CPR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)]<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> containing bridging phosphoniodithio-carboxylates as ligands are formed. [(PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)Pd(S<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>CPMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)]<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> is also obtained from (PR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>Pd(η<jats:sup>2</jats:sup> -CS<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>) (PR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> = PPr<jats:sup>i</jats:sup><jats:sub>3</jats:sub>, PMePh<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>, PPh<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>) and PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>. The reactions of Pd(PR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)<jats:sub>n</jats:sub> with the zwitter ions PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>CS<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> and PMe<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>PhCS<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> lead to binuclear compounds [(PR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)Pd(S<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>CPR′<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)]<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> (PR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> = PPr<jats:sup>i</jats:sup><jats:sub>3</jats:sub>, PMe<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>Ph, PMePh<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>, PPh<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>; PR′<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> = PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>, and PR<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> = PMePh<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>; PR′<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> = PMe<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>Ph). [(PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)Pd(S<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>CPMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)]<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> reacts with PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> with cleavage of the phosphoniodithiocarboxylate bridges to give (PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>Pd(S<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>CPMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>). The formation of [(PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)Ni(S<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>CPMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)]<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> from Ni(PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>)<jats:sub>4</jats:sub> and PMe<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>CS<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> is also described.</jats:p>
